segments.text: The moment she opened her eyes, the sharp scent of guavas wafted through the open window.
She lay awake, letting herself calm down from her restless night's sleep.
After choosing a room, she had cleaned it and settled in, but couldn't manage to sleep until late, excited by the idea of sleeping again in her house.
For a moment, she was seized with anxiety about the audacity of renting the rooms to the group of young people, realizing she had overdone it.
She knew there was no turning back and promised herself it wouldn't happen again.
Ultimately, her fatigue won over.
But now, as soon as she smelled the guavas, she knew she was home.
Even a scent is home.
She stared at the open window through which that heavy aroma entered, thinking about Michael's father, the landscape architect who designed the beautiful green neighborhood around her.
What exactly was he thinking when he filled their lovely neighborhood with guava trees?

He easily convinced the new residents it was a tree fond of sand growing tall and produced an abundance of fruit with medicinal properties rich in iron and vitamins and tasted like a cross between an apple and a pear.
All true, except he forgot to mention that the fruit has such a strong smell, there's no escaping it.
And ever since, whenever autumn ended and winter began, Affectar neighborhood was filled with the strong scent of the many guava trees planted in the yards.
For a month each year, all the neighborhood residents dealt with this controversial fruit.
They wrapped it in brown paper bags to prevent the birds from eating it, and the meticulous among them doubled the wrappings, hoping it might contain the fruit's smell too.
Of course, it didn't help.

If that wasn't enough, every child showed up with a guava in their bag for a ten o'clock snack, received crushed guava for stomach or throat aches, and Sephora the neighbor insisted the fruit worked wonders even for curing hemorrhoids.
Lucy found endless uses for guavas.
She added them to meatball mixtures, fruit compote, and excelled at making guava strudel.
Tons of fruit that cost nothing and provided refreshments for the entire neighborhood, but in the same breath, perfumed it with a heavy, unbearable aroma.
Thus, the neighborhood divided into two, guava lovers and guava haters.
She still stared at the open window.
Wondering how she savored eating this fruit despite hating its smell, realizing she actually belonged to a third group, those who detest the guava smell but delight in its taste.
She remembered how Lucy was enchanted by the abundant fruit around her, belonging to the group in love with it, marveling at her surroundings and saying to Yosef,
Look at the wonderful place we live in.
We have a fig tree growing on its own in the yard.
Large sycamore and mulberry trees in the garden and great finds on the dune.
Even domed trees, I don't know what they are.
And now, also guava trees.
He would laugh heartily and say, it's a real paradise.
Together with Shlomo the milkman, it's truly a land flowing with milk and honey.
I can't stand this smell.
If I could, I'd escape for a month from this guava city.
But Lucy remained joyful, and for a month each year she packed every guest leaving the pink house, with a farewell gift, a bag of guavas for the road.
A short while after she got up, she made her way to the corner of the garden, picked a ripe guava, wiped it with her hand, and took a mouthful bite of the fruit of paradise.
It was still early and she stood in the kitchen to prepare breakfast for the young men.
She chopped a salad, sliced bread, placed green olives in a dish.
In another dish, she set slices of yellow cheese and in another, a block of butter.
And she moved to the dining room, spread a cloth over one of the tables and set plates, cups and cutlery on it.
She went out to the garden and found some chrysanthemum flowers growing wild by the hedge, picked them, made a small bouquet, placed it in a beer glass and put it in the center of the table.
Her heart sang, this is how she wanted it, just like it was at Lucy's.
She still had time until they woke up.
She made herself a cup of coffee with milk in the large beer glass, held it in both hands and relished it.
She felt wonderful as though she had recovered from some illness, as if her wounded heart had healed and was beating strongly again.
Deep down, she knew it was a fleeting illusion.
But what did it matter to her?
This, just for now, was good enough for her.
For now.
She used her free time with the laundry.
She folded the sheets, towels, uniforms, short pants, and the grandad vest she washed after yesterday's cleaning.
Luckily, she had long pants and a white t-shirt in her bag, which she wore now.
She was neatly groomed with her braid tied back, not unkempt like yesterday.
Yet her feet remained bare.
That's how she liked it.
In the niche at the kitchen entrance, she noticed the ironing board and iron beside it.
He really left everything behind, her dear daddy.
It was hard for her to grasp.
Some things over the years become very personal.
How can they be left behind?
But now she was glad she could iron her uniform and head out the next morning looking neat and organized.
She turned on the radio and was surprised to hear Shoshana Damari's pleasant voice emerging from it, as if by invitation.
Her heart filled with warmth.
She had so many childhood memories of Shoshana, who was a close friend of Lucy when they both worked in theater.
Lucy would call her.
For a moment, a smile crossed her lips.
When there are flowers on the table and music in her ears, life is as it should be.
She stood with her back to the entrance when she heard them proclaim in unison.
Good morning!
And then turned to them with a smiling, good morning of her own.
How did you sleep?
She asked.
I heard you came back very late.
I hope you enjoyed the small town.
We enjoyed very much and also slept wonderfully.
The quiet here rings in our ears.
And if we didn't have to continue our trip, we'd probably sleep until noon.
What a lovely table you've set for us, one of them said.
Yes, unfortunately, because of the renovations, the garden is a bit wilted, but chrysanthemums grow on their own and there are plenty.
She thought to herself how easily lies slipped from her mouth without stumbling.
Would you like omelets?
Yes, sure, they answered again in unison.
She smiled to herself and said aloud, You're so synchronized with your answers, you could be a choir.
They all laughed loudly.
That's what happens after three years together, 24 hours a day.
You become in sync.
Shortly after, she walked to the table with their omelets and watched as they ravenously devoured the breakfast.
She placed a glass of orange juice beside each of them, returned to the kitchen, and brought them a coffee pot with a small milk jug.
Again, she returned to the kitchen, unsure of what to do.
She didn't want to cling to them, and was also afraid they'd start asking too many questions.
So she remained standing in the kitchen, leaning on the counter beside the hatch between the kitchen and the dining room.
Through this hatch, they used to pass plates when the dining room was full of campers, especially during the summer months.
She peeked through and saw them engrossed in cheerful conversation, planning the day's trip.
She gazed thoughtfully through the hatch and suddenly a vivid memory of age five surfaced, where she had once seen Ben Goryan's white mane through the hatch.
Without realizing, she burst into laughter, completely forgetting the young men and herself.
A minute later, she went out to clear the table and see if they wanted anything else.
Something really amused you beyond the wall, commented the first one from yesterday.
She smiled to herself.

I remembered something from many years ago when I was five, she said embarrassed, something I saw through this hatch, which in my childhood I called the peeking hatch, because I'd stand on a box beside my mother in the kitchen and peek to see what was happening in the dining room.
She got a bit carried away.
What was she rambling to them?
Well, can we know what you saw that was so amusing?
She realized she couldn't back out.
Ben Gurion's white mane, the first one got up, drew a chair to their table and gestured invitingly for her to join them.
Strange, but she felt comfortable with them.
They weren't much older than she was.
And they were on their release holiday.
She sat down with them.
This house once hosted all the greats of the nation and the Bohemia.
And for me, this hatch was a world of surprises, she told them.
When the dining room was full, I'd play a game of counting the heads, peeking at the important figures who arrived here.
a world full of experiences and stories passed through this little hatch.
But the story of Ben-Gurion's white mane is probably the first I remember.
Ben-Gurion finished a visit to Ashkelon, accompanied by a whole entourage, and was supposed to come here for lunch.
The place buzzed with excitement, preparing for his arrival.
The dining room was cleared.
A few tables were joined.
covered with white cloths, and vases of flowers were placed.
Mom was busy at a kitchen with the pots, asking me repeatedly not to get underfoot.
I'm not under, I'm beside, I told her.
I was also excited.
Every child knew who Ben-Gurion was.
Ben-Gurion is very important.
Is he like a king?
I asked my mom and she laughed.
Yes, like a king, sort of.
So I peeked through the hatch and saw his white hair with his back to me surrounded by many heads.
I played the counting game and counted eight heads.
Suddenly, a woman with clattering shoes entered the kitchen.
said hello, lifted pot lids, sniffed here and there, and said, great.
She shook my mom's hand and left.
Mom explained she was Ben Gourian's wife and her name was Paula.
With Paula, I had nine heads, but only one was white Ben Gourian's.
After they finished the compote, mom removed her apron, went out to join dad.
He came into the kitchen for a moment.
lifted me off the box where I stood peeking, took my hand and brought me to say hello to Ben-Gurion.
Ben-Gurion shook my small hand like they do with grownups.
What's your name?
He asked.
Leora, I told him.
And how old are you?
Five.
Which grade are you in?
Well, here's something almost tragic occurred.
I turned quickly to my dad and said loudly and with great disappointment.
What kind of Ben-Gurion doesn't know that at five you don't go to school?
For me, I discovered that moment that the king was naked.
One of the nine heads I counted earlier belonged to journalist Azaria Rapaport, who the next day published a headline in the newspaper.
What kind of Ben Gurion is this?
And that's what made me laugh.
I suddenly remembered this as I peeked through the hatch to see if you'd finished eating.
She lifted her head towards them, hugely embarrassed, realizing she had spilled over, feeling like some old.
tedious woman dwelling on her memories, but to her surprise, she found four pairs of eyes smiling joyfully at her.
What a story, they said, in their usual chorus.
A bit later, they got up, thanked her, noting they'd return around seven for dinner.
Yesterday evening, as it began to darken, and the yellowish light above the chair cast light on the pictures that had returned to the bare walls, she approached the phone and called Yosef.
Hey dad, I didn't want you to worry.
I went to Ashkelon to visit Zvik of Carmella as I promised him.
I had no idea he passed away two days ago.
I'm so sad about this, I can't describe what I feel in my heart.
To suddenly give two coughs and die?
She paused momentarily and heard him say,
Mominka, you know, maybe it's better this way.
To close your eyes and die without suffering.
Interestingly, that's exactly what she thought too.
They both remember well how much suffering it could entail.
How are you?
He asked after a moment, how is the graduation ceremony of the course?
When can I see you a little?
I'm really missing you.
For a moment, she wanted to tell him that she missed him too, because it was true.
But the meetings at his home with his partner didn't go well.
Something between them didn't settle.
She herself made every effort to behave nicely and politely.
She tried hard, but it was never good enough for his partner.
And a note or remark of dissatisfaction always came out.
She felt a bit offended.
Every time she was there, she found herself mainly intense, oppressive silence.
She was saddened to see her father's helplessness before his partner, who didn't let anyone forget it was her home and they'd always remain guests in it.
She didn't want to be her guest.
More than anything, she wanted to tell him where she was but wasn't sure he'd understand.
For now, it was her secret.
Already for a while, he thinks she's sleeping at one friend's or another's place.
Their meetings move to Jackie's cafe at Chen Boulevard corner in Tel Aviv, not far from the apartment he lived in.
Every other weekend.
Please write to me, sweetheart.
I'll also write you and send a package with goodies you like.
Do you need anything?
No, Daddy.
I don't need anything.
Thanks, she answered, feeling a lump of sadness form in her throat, said bye and hung up.
There's something in the feeling of loneliness that penetrates deeply into the bloodstream, almost aching the muscles, a pain that cannot be explained.
She sank into the chair and surrendered to it, letting her heart calm down and compose itself.
When she finally whiffed at her head, she met Lucy's eyes, looking from the portrait deep into her own.
And instantly she calmed.
Everything is okay.
She was home, even if only for now.
At exactly seven, the young men entered for dinner, clean and polished after a shower.
Their hair was still damp, and they seemed ready for inspection, smiling at her and saying again, almost in chorus,
What a smell!
She seated them at the table and went to the kitchen to bring the food.
She had a feeling the first one was looking at her in a slightly odd way, as if he wanted to tell her something, but remained silent.
In a moment's decision, she poured the entire contents of the goulash pot into a large bowl, placed the potatoes on a separate serving dish and brought everything to their table.
Listen, instead of me serving you portions, just take as much as you'd like until you're full.
They smiled, and in a moment, pounced on the food on the table.
Would you like beer?
She asked.
Gladly, they replied.
She went behind the bar, poured them beer into large glasses, tilting them as she was used to, so no foam would form.
When she served them the beer glasses, again she felt the first one was looking at her seriously, assessing.
She found herself once more in the kitchen, behind the wall, giving them time alone without clinging to them, afraid she'd start telling her stories again, and maybe some she didn't want to share.
She poured herself a glass of water into the large beer glass she loved, sipping slowly, waiting for time to pass.
Suddenly she saw the first one at the kitchen entrance.
Listen, I have to ask you something.
I met a friend by the sea while we walked.
He asked where we were staying.
I told him at the pink house and he was very surprised.
He didn't know it was reopened and said the house has been closed for months since it was sold.
Then I remembered that when we arrived, the walls were still bare of paintings.
But when we got here in the morning, all the paintings were hung on the wall.
Are you running this place again?"
She paled completely, almost choked by his question, squirmed, unsure how to react.
Yes, but only for now, she said in an unstable voice.
Aren't you a little too young for this?
He asked quietly.
Not really, she replied in a tone that asked to end the conversation.
He looked at her deeply, trying to ease her, a shadow of a smile crossing his lips.
Well, then good luck to you," he said, and left the kitchen.
Now she was completely entangled.
Suddenly she just wanted them to leave already, so she could clean up after them and restore things as if they had never been.
She went out to them, cleared the tableware, not daring to look at the first one, trying to keep her voice light, as she asked.
Was it tasty?
It was.
Wonderful!
They responded in their usual chorus.
She was relieved.
There's ice cream for dessert, she said.
They were very pleased.
Then it became apparent they had no intention of going to sleep anytime soon.

They sat on the bar chairs and asked for more beers, watching her open mouthed every time she poured them beer professionally, tilting the glass, bringing them olives to accompany and engaging in casual small talk.
They told her they'd been friends since high school and went through the entire military path together, even officer training.
And before deciding on each of their life paths, wanted to take a joint trip.
From here, they were heading south to Elat.
The first one asked her to prepare the bill because they would leave the hotel early in the morning and might not see her.
What to do now?
How to calculate?
two rooms, four young men, four breakfasts, four dinners, 12 beers, four black coffees.
She went to the reception counter, took a note, and wrote down prices lower than she remembered, summed it up, and saw that after the shopping she did, there was more than enough.
When she lifted her head from the paper, she saw him leaning on the reception counter and handed him the bill.
Is this everything?
He was surprised.
Yes, what?
Did I forget something?
No, but it seems particularly cheap.
Well, she smiled, we have a special price for soldiers.
When he returned to her after collecting money from his friends, she noticed they paid her more and said, I don't have change to give you.
He laughed.
That's alright.
It's our tip for the great pleasure we had at this place and the pampering you gave us.
Thank you very much.
They were already standing at the entrance, bidding her goodbye, thanking her in chorus.
Only the first one, approached and quietly said to her,
Good luck and take care of yourself."
Added a good night wish and left.
Shortly after they left, everything was clean and orderly.
She scrubbed the pots, washed the dishes, wiped down, returned everything to its place, then took a glass jar from the kitchen and placed some of the money in it.
The rest she tucked into her pocket, knowing she'd earned it almost honestly.
Then she went to the bar and poured herself a beer.
It had been so long since she drank beer ever since Rolf left.
Something in her wanted to feel that cold bitterness slipping down her throat.
Slowly, she sipped, sitting on the bar chair, gazing around the clean and orderly room.
at the paintings on the walls and for a brief moment lived the for now.
It was very early morning.
The scent of autumn was in the air and she felt a slight chill in her limbs.
She was already gathered in her ironed uniform, her braid tightly pinned to her head and her few belongings packed in her small bag ready for her return to the army.
As usual, she awoke early, so time was on her side.
She made herself a cup of coffee with milk and a heaping teaspoon of sugar.
Sat relaxed, gazing around at the clean and orderly home she was leaving behind after a stormy, exciting and strange weekend.
She went to the reception counter, rummaged in the lower shelf, and pulled out a clean sheet featuring the pink house logo.
She took a pen from her bag and wrote, Hello, Yehuda.
The past two days I spent again in the house brought me immense joy and warmed my heart.
As you will see, I cleaned and scrubbed everywhere, and in a moment of uncontrollable whim, also hung dad's pictures back on the walls.
The pictures instantly turned the place back into the pink house.
I'm sorry, but it seems I crossed a red line in a careless moment when I rented out two rooms to four soldiers looking for a place to rest their heads.
Not only that, but I also prepared them breakfast and cook dinner.
Something inside rebelled out of spite and I couldn't say no to them.
I hope you will forgive me and promise not to repeat it without your permission.
In the jar on the counter, I left the majority of what they paid me.
The rest covered the shopping at Albert's grocery store, and I kept a few coins for pocket money.
I hope you understand and won't be too.
Angry, you have no idea how grateful I am that you allowed me to stay in the house.
Thank you for everything, Leora.
She carefully folded the letter, wrote to Yahuda in large letters, and propped it against the jars we couldn't miss it when he entered.
Deep down, she hoped he'd understand, wouldn't be mad.
She cast one last satisfied glance around, took her belongings, locked the door, and set out on her way, knowing she had some place to return to next week.
